Tidyverse Overview

The tidyverse is a family of packages that share a similar grammar, syntax, and data structure. This similarity in programming style allows for an easy transition from learning one package to the next and from utilizing many packages to accomplish complicated tasks.

The tidyverse is built to help you accomplish all tasks within the data analysis pipeline ranging from data collection and cleaning all the way to data visualization and analysis.

This tutorial will describe the various packages that are included in the tidyverse and will give some simple examples of how to use the key packages.

Packages Included in the Tidyverse

The following list is not every package that is downloaded when you install the tidyverse, but these are some of the main packages that are highly useful in everyday data analysis tasks:

  • readr - The readr package allows you to read in data that are coming from typical data formats, such as fixed width data and csv files.

  • dplyr - The dplyr package supplies a series of functions to aid in data manipulation and cleaning.

  • ggplot2 - The ggplot2 package provides a Grammar of Graphics that allows you to create highly customizable visualizations layer by layer.

  • tidyr - The tidyr package provides a series of functions to tidy your dataset and create a clean, easy to analyze/visualize dataset.

  • purrr - purrr enhances Rs functional programming (FP) toolkit by providing a complete and consistent set of tools for working with functions and vectors. Once you master the basic concepts, purrr allows you to replace many for loops with code that is easier to write and more expressive.

  • stringr - The stringr package provides a series of functions that allow you to manipulate string/character variables. Very useful for complex, messy datasets.

  • forcats - The forcats package gives a series of functions that helps the user deal with the usual issues that arise when using factors.

Installing the Tidyverse

To get started with the tidyverse, you need to run the install.packages function to download the tidyverse from the CRAN.

install.packages("tidyverse")

You then need to load the packages so that you can use the associated functions.

library(tidyverse)

Note: After loading the library, you might get warnings that you have conflicts. These occur when a function of the same name exists in two different packages. To ensure you are using the function you mean to, you can use the package_name::function_name syntax.

dplyr::filter(varA > 50)

readr

As mentioned earlier, the readr package provides the functionality to read data in from common data files. The main functions that I will discuss in this tutorial, are the read_csv() and write_csv() functions. These functions help you to read in and write out files to and from csv files. They behave quite similar to the read_delim, read_fwf, etc. functions. Below, we are going to read in data from the National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey and save it as an object.

nh <- read_csv("https://davidmartinconsulting.github.io/Compendium/nhanes.csv")

The main input that is necessary for the read_csv function is the location of the file that you want to use.

For the write_csv function, you need to supply the object that you would like to export and the name and location of the new file you want to create.

write_csv(nh, "nhanes.csv")

One final note for the readr package is that when using the read_ functions, you will import the dataset as a tibble instead of a dataframe.

class(nh)
## [1] "spec_tbl_df" "tbl_df"      "tbl"         "data.frame"

Tibbles are similar to dataframes, however, they have some additional aesthetic improvements and they can often convert columns to different data types than you would expect from a dataframe.

dplyr functions

dplyr is a package in R that allows you to work with and manipulate your data. It allows you to focus in on the variables (columns) of interest and the observations (rows) of interest.

Using The Pipe

The pipe is an operator in R that allows you to chain together functions in dplyr. In the past, to use multiple functions you would have to nest your functions inside of each other, but using the pipe allows you to chain the functions together in a readable/reproducible format. The pipe character is %>% and essentially means then You can create the character using CTRL+SHIFT+M or CMD+SHIFT+M. The pipe essentially takes whatever is before the pipe as input for whatever is after the pipe.

# Normal way to view your dataset
View(nh)

# Using the pipe, the nh dataframe is passed on to the View function
nh %>% 
  View()

# The head function looks at the top of the dataframe

arrange

The arrange() function does what it sounds like. It takes a data frame or tbl and arranges (or sorts) by column(s) of interest. The first argument is the data, and subsequent arguments are columns to sort on. Use the desc() function to arrange by descending.

The following code would get the number of times each state shows up in the nh dataset:

nh %>% 
  count(Education) %>% 
  arrange(n)
## # A tibble: 6  2
##   Education          n
##   <chr>          <int>
## 1 8th Grade        451
## 2 9 - 11th Grade   888
## 3 High School     1517
## 4 College Grad    2098
## 5 Some College    2267
## 6 <NA>            2779
# Since the default is ascending order, we are not getting the results that are probably useful, so let's use the desc() function
nh %>% 
  count(Education) %>% 
  arrange(desc(n))
## # A tibble: 6  2
##   Education          n
##   <chr>          <int>
## 1 <NA>            2779
## 2 Some College    2267
## 3 College Grad    2098
## 4 High School     1517
## 5 9 - 11th Grade   888
## 6 8th Grade        451

filter

If you want to filter rows of the data where some condition is true, use the filter() function.

  1. The first argument is the dataset you want to filter, e.g.filter(mydata, ....
  2. The second argument is a condition you must satisfy, e.g.filter(clean, variable == "levelA").
  • ==: Equal to
  • !=: Not equal to
  • >, >=: Greater than, greater than or equal to
  • <, <=: Less than, less than or equal to

If you want to satisfy all of multiple conditions, you can use the and operator, &. The or operator | (the pipe character, usually shift-backslash) will return a subset that meet any of the conditions.

#Keeps those patients younger than 30 
nh %>%

summarize

The summarize() function summarizes multiple values to a single value. On its own the summarize() function doesnt seem to be all that useful. The dplyr package provides a few convenience functions called n() and n_distinct() that tell you the number of observations or the number of distinct values of a particular variable.

Notice that summarize takes a data frame and returns a data frame. In this case its a 1x1 data frame with a single row and a single column. The name of the column, by default is whatever the expression was used to summarize the data. This usually isnt pretty, and if we wanted to work with this resulting data frame later on, wed want to name that returned value something easier to deal with.

nh %>% 
  summarize(mean(Age))
## # A tibble: 1  1
##   `mean(Age)`
##         <dbl>
## 1        36.7
#Gotta watch out for nas. Use na.rm = TRUE to run the calculation without nas being involved.
nh %>% 
  summarize(mean(Weight))
## # A tibble: 1  1
##   `mean(Weight)`
##            <dbl>
## 1             NA
nh %>% 
  summarize(mean(Weight, na.rm = TRUE))
## # A tibble: 1  1
##   `mean(Weight, na.rm = TRUE)`
##                          <dbl>
## 1                         71.0
#The default column names do not look very aesthetically pleasing, let's take care of that.
nh %>% 
  summarize(Weight = mean(Weight, na.rm = TRUE))
## # A tibble: 1  1
##   Weight
##    <dbl>
## 1   71.0
#Again, summarize alone is not entirely useful
nh %>% 
  summarize(n())
## # A tibble: 1  1
##   `n()`
##   <int>
## 1 10000

The real power comes in where group_by() and summarize() are used together. First, write the group_by() statement. Then pipe the result to a call to summarize().

#Let's summarize the mean weight of patients for each Education Level

  group_by(Education) %>%

ggplot2

ggplot2 is a widely used R package that extends Rs visualization capabilities. It takes the hassle out of things like creating legends, mapping other variables to scales like color, or faceting plots into small multiples. Well learn about what all these things mean shortly.

Specifically, ggplot2 allows you to build a plot layer-by-layer by specifying:

  • a geom, which specifies how the data are represented on the plot (points, lines, bars, etc.),
  • aesthetics that map variables in the data to axes on the plot or to plotting size, shape, color, etc.,
  • facets, which weve already seen above, that allow the data to be divided into chunks on the basis of other categorical or continuous variables and the same plot drawn for each chunk.

The ggplot function has two required arguments: the data used for creating the plot, and an aesthetic mapping to describe how variables in said data are mapped to things we can see on the plot.

First, lets lay out the plot. If we want to plot a continuous Y variable by a continuous X variable were probably most interested in a scatter plot. Here, were telling ggplot that we want to use the nh dataset, and the aesthetic mapping will map Weight onto the x-axis and Testosterone onto the y-axis. We are going to only focus on male patients for these charts, so we need to use the filter function from above to create a male only dataset and we are going to grab just the top 1500 patients

nh_m <- nh %>% filter(Gender == "male" & !is.na(Testosterone)) %>% head(1500)

# The ggplot function creates an initial canvas
ggplot(data =  nh_m, aes(x = Weight, y = Testosterone))

When we do that we get a blank canvas with no data showing. Thats because all weve done is laid out a two-dimensional plot specifying what goes on the x and y axes, but we havent told it what kind of geometric object to plot. The obvious choice here is a point. Check out docs.ggplot2.org to see what kind of geoms are available.

Add geom_point()

ggplot(data =  nh_m, aes(x = Weight, y = Testosterone)) + 
  geom_point()

Lets add some color by changing all the points to be blue. By looking at the geom_point function in the help menu, you can see that their are several arguments/options that you can change within the geom. This is true for every geom that we will explore today and others that you might explore on your own.

The colors() function will provide you all of the colors that are initially available in R.

# colors()
# Here the color = "blue" argument will make every point blue. This argument will behave differently depending on the type of geom you are using.
ggplot(data =  nh_m, aes(x = Weight, y = Testosterone)) +
  geom_point(color = "blue")

Instead of coloring by a static value, lets color by Race (Race1). Remember that any time you want to map a variable onto the plot, it must be in a call to aes()

# Notice that color is no longer a single value (ie: blue), but the value of a given category. This will now create a different color point for each value found in a category. 
ggplot(data =  nh_m, aes(x = Weight, y = Testosterone)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color = Race1))

Lets add another layer showing a smoothed trend line. (and lets go back to the normal geom_point shape). Remember, that each new layer will go on top of the previous one, meaning that the smoothed line will go on top of the points.

# Use a + sign to connect together ggplot elements such as a geom.
ggplot(data =  nh_m, aes(x = Weight, y = Testosterone)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color = Race1)) +
  geom_smooth()

Notice that geom_smooth() is fitting the trend line using a gam Model.

# ?geom_smooth

Look at the Arguments section and read the bit about the method argument. We can specify a method, but if we allow the method = "auto" then it will fit loess for < 1000 data points and general additive models gam for >= 1000

Lets change the method to be lm to fit a straight line using the method argument

ggplot(data =  nh_m, aes(x = Weight, y = Testosterone)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color = Race1))+
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")

Lets fit a smoothed line (allowing the default method = auto) separately for each Race

# Notice that we have aesthetic mappings (aes) in both the point geom and the smooth geom.
ggplot(data =  nh_m, aes(x = Weight, y = Testosterone)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color = Race1)) +
  geom_smooth(aes(color = Race1))

In the above code we now have three calls to aes(). One in the canvas layer, one in the geom_point() layer, and one in the geom_smooth() layer.

If we want ALL the layers to be colored by Race, we can just specify color = Race1 in the top canvas layer and all the subsequent layers will inherit that aesthetic mapping just like they inherit the x and y from the canvas layer.

# I've added lwd = 2 to the geom_smooth() function to create a thicker fitted line.
ggplot(data = nh_m, aes(x = Weight, y = Testosterone, color = Race1)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(lwd = 2, se = FALSE) 

# se = FALSE removes standard error bars

Facets

Facets display subsets of the data in different panels. There are a couple ways to do this, but facet_wrap() tries to sensibly wrap a series of facets into a 2-dimensional grid of small multiples.

The facet functions take a formula specifying which variables to facet by. If you have a look at the help for ?facet_wrap() youll see that we can control how the wrapping is laid out.

Along the way to teaching you about faceting, Ill show a strategy to build up a plot by saving layers you like to an object. This way, we can avoid having to copy-paste long lines of code.

Lets start with a simple plot of Weight x and Testosterone on y.

Lets create the canvas and then save that to object called p.

p <- ggplot(nh_m, aes(x = Weight, y = Testosterone))
p + geom_point()

Well facet by Race1 to show each Race in its own plot. Notice that we use the ~ in front of Race1. facet_wrap uses a formula as input, and the ~ is used when creating a formula.

# You could put another category in front of the ~ to create factorial graphs
p + geom_point() + 
  facet_wrap(~Race1)

Plotting univariate continuous data

What if we just wanted to visualize distribution of a single continuous variable? A histogram is the usual go-to visualization. Here we only have one aesthetic mapping instead of two.

# Let's investigate the distribution of the Testosterone variable
# set this as the canvas
p <- nh_m %>% ggplot(aes(Testosterone))
p + geom_histogram()

We change the number of bins that we have in our histograms. Generally, you want to do this utilizing prior knowledge or research.

# We can either use the bins option to specify the number of bins or you can use the bin.width option to specify the width of the bins.
p + geom_histogram(bins = 50)

p + geom_histogram(bins = 10)

p + geom_histogram(binwidth = 1)

We can also color the bars by our Race1 variable.

p + geom_histogram(aes(color = Race1))

Well, that is not exactly what I meant. I wanted the inside of the bars colored. That argument is fill instead of color, just like with box plots.

p + geom_histogram(aes(fill = Race1))

If you look at the help for ?geom_histogram youll see that by default it stacks overlapping data, so if two Races have the same Testosterone, one is plotted on the bottom and the second is plotted stacked on top of the first. This is a misleading visualization for that reason. Lets change the position argument so that each Race has a baseline of 0.

# Here we use position = "identity"
p + geom_histogram(aes(fill = Race1), position = "identity")

Thats better, but still not great. Lets use alpha to change the transparancy

p + geom_histogram(aes(fill = Race1), position = "identity", alpha = .3)

Maybe better, but lets try faceting instead.

p + geom_histogram(aes(fill = Race1), position = "identity") + 
  facet_wrap(~Race1)

Great!

Lets start back at p and plot a smoothed density curve instead of a histogram.

p + geom_density()

Now color that by the Race1

p + geom_density(aes(color = Race1))

This could work for a couple of groups, but with 3 or more, it can get a bit busy. Lets facet

p + geom_density(aes(color = Race1)) +
  facet_wrap(~Race1)

Change color to fill and you will see that instead of the outline being colored, the whole curve is filled

p + geom_density(aes(fill = Race1)) +
  facet_wrap(~Race1)

Saving plots

There are a few ways to save ggplots. The quickest way, that works in an interactive session, is to use the ggsave() function. You give it a file name and by default it saves the last plot that was printed to the screen.

ggsave(file = "testost_race.png")

Where did it go? You will see that it went directly into your project folder. Typically, I would prefer to have a directory structure that has my code, images, results, etc. all separated out.

In a script, the best way to do it is to pass ggsave() the object containing the plot that is meant to be saved. We can also adjust things like the width, height, and resolution. ggsave() also recognizes the name of the file extension and saves the appropriate kind of file. Lets save a PDF.

# I am first going to create a single column of graphs so that each graph in the facet wrap gets its own row
pfinal <- p + 
  geom_density(aes(fill = Race1)) +
  facet_wrap(~Race1, ncol = 1)
pfinal
ggsave(pfinal, file = "test_race.pdf", width = 7, height = 12)

Publication ready graphics

Lets keep using our density plot and add some useful aesthetic elements.

# create the canvas
# add the layers and save them onto p
p <- nh_m %>% ggplot(aes(Testosterone)) +
  geom_density(aes(fill = Race1)) +
  facet_wrap(~Race1)

p

Lets add proper axes labels using labs(). Keep adding to create a title, subtitle, and better legend title (color).

# save the labs onto p
p <- p + labs(x = "Testosterone Levels", 
         y = "Density of Values",
         title = "Testosterone Levels",
         subtitle = "By Race", 
         fill = "Race")
p

The author of ggplot2, Hadley Wickham has chosen the gray theme as the default, but there are others that automatically make some aesthetic choices for you.

p + theme_bw()

p + theme_classic()

Creating your own themes

If you wanted to, you can also customize your own plots using the theme function. Within this function there are thousands of combinations that you can choose to aesthetically change your graphs, ranging from the color of your titles to the shape of the outline of the legend. I tend to use the a built-in theme, generally theme_classic and then make a few additions from there. I will only give a small example of how to do this, but to cover all of the things you could do in this function would take days/weeks.

#?theme
mytheme <- theme(axis.title.x = element_text(color = "red"), 
                 panel.background = element_rect(color = "orange", 
                                                 fill = "turquoise4", 
                                                 linetype = "longdash")
                )

p + theme_classic() + mytheme

Sometimes you may want to go outside of the colors that ggplot provides for you when filling in histograms, coloring points, etc. Fortunately, plenty of tools are provided to customize these color sets.

#colors()
p + scale_fill_viridis_d()

p + scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Greens")

p + scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set1")

#?scale_fill_brewer()

p + scale_fill_manual(values = c("purple", "black", "gold", "green", "orange"))

nh_m %>% ggplot(aes(Weight, Testosterone, color = Testosterone)) +
  geom_point(size = 4) +
  scale_color_gradient(low  = "blue", high = "red")

To create a connected line graph you simply need to add the geom_line following the geom_point. However, this will not always work as intended.

gm %>% 
  ggplot(aes(year, lifeExp)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_line()

The geom_line function works best with summarized/grouped data.

gm %>% 
  group_by(continent, year) %>% 
  summarize(lifeExp = mean(lifeExp, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(year, lifeExp, color = continent)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_line()

Below, I have customized a connected line chart using the ggrepel package. This package contains the geom_text_repel function that allows you to add text to your plots in an efficient manner. To ensure that the label does not show up at every point in the graph, I created a label variable that will only be created for the year 2007.

install.packages("ggrepel")
library(ggrepel)
gm %>% 
  group_by(continent, year) %>% 
  summarize(lifeExp = mean(lifeExp, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  mutate(label = if_else(year == 2007, paste0(continent), "")) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(year, lifeExp, color = continent)) + 
  geom_point(size = 2) + 
  geom_line(size = 1) + 
  geom_text_repel(aes(label = label), 
                  size = 5) +
  theme_classic() + 
  theme(legend.position = "none",
        axis.text = element_text(size = 10)) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(min(gm$year),
                                max(gm$year),
                                5)) +
  labs(x = "Year", y = "Life Expectancy (years)")

Finally, notice the scale_x_continuous function. Using the seq function I was able to create axis ticks that match up directly with the min/max and intervals that are in the dataset. The scale family of functions are very helpful for changing the way the axes are laid out.
